
  gmail.py - interact with Gmail through python
  ---------------------------------------------

- gmail.py wraps imaplib and smtplib to make it easier to interact with
  your Gmail account through python.

- Examples:

    - Login (this automatically connects to IMAP and SMTP) and then out:

        > import gmail
        > conn = gmail.Gmail('username', 'password')
        > # do stuff...
        > conn.logout()

    - Interact with labels:
        
        > conn.labels.switch('sent')
        1567 # Number of emails in that label
        > conn.labels.create('mylabel')
        > conn.labels.exists('foo')
        False
        > len(conn.labels.all())
        25

    - Download email:
        
        > msgs = conn.unread()
        > msgs 
        [<gmail.Message object...]

    - Send email:

        > msg = gmail.Message().fill('you@gmail.com', 'me@gmail.com',
        ... 'fwd: fwd: funny', 'pictures of cats')
        > msg.to_addresses()
        ['you@gmail.com']
        > msg.subject()
        'fwd: fwd: funny'
        > conn.send(msg)

- Notes:

    - Downloading, searching and fetching email is the roughest part of the 
      project so far and is liable to change.

    - Messages are not downloaded when you make a call such as 'conn.unread()'.
      This creates Message objects that store the message id and a reference
      to your IMAP connection.  When you first try to read anything from them,
      they download.

